.TH SIMPLE_SHELL

.SH NAME
simple_shell, a simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter that reads and executes commands from standard input or from a pipeline.
It replicates the basic behavior of
.B /bin/ls
and supports both in interactive and non-interactive mode.

In
.B interactive mode,
the shell displays a prompt and waits for the user to type a command.
The prompt is displayed again after each command is executed.

In
.B non-interactive mode,
the shell reads commands from a pipe or a file without displaying a prompt.

.SH USAGE
.TP
Interactive mode:
.B $ ./hsh
.br
.B ($) /bin/ls
.br
.B ($) exit

.TP
Non-interactive mode:
.B $ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell. The shell terminates with the exit status of the last command executed.

.TP
.B env
Print the current environment. Displays all environment variables in the format NAME=value.

.SH COMMAND EXECUTION
When a command is entered, the shell performs the following steps:

.IP 1.
Read the command line using
.BR getline (3).
.IP 2.
Parse the command line into tokens using
.BR strtok (3).
.IP 3.
Check if the command is a builtin. If so, execute it directly.
.IP 4.
Search for the command executable in the directories listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable using
.BR access (2).
.IP 5.
If found, create a child process using
.BR fork (2)
and execute the command using
.BR execve (2).
.IP 6.
The parent process waits for the child to finish using
.BR wait (2).

.SH PATH
The shell searches for commands in the directories listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable.
If the command is given as an absolute or relative path (e.g.
.IR /bin/ls
or
.IR ./myscript ),
the PATH search is skipped.
If the command is not found in any directory listed in PATH, an error message is printed and no child process is created.

.SH ERROR HANDLING
If a command cannot be found, the shell prints an error to standard error in the following format:

.RS
.B argv[0]: LINE_NUMBER: COMMAND: not found
.RE

Example:
.RS
.B ./hsh: 1: qwerty: not found
.RE

.SH SIGNALS
.TP
.B Ctrl+C
Does not exit the shell (SIGINT is ignored in the main process).
.TP
.B Ctrl+D
Signals end of file (EOF) and exits the shell cleanly.

.SH COMPILATION
.B gcc -Wall -Werror -Wextra -pedantic -std=gnu89 *.c -o hsh

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Run a command with arguments:
.B ($) ls -la /tmp

.TP
Use an absolute path:
.B ($) /bin/echo Hello World

.TP
Display environment variables:
.B ($) env

.TP
Exit the shell:
.B ($) exit

.TP
Non-interactive with a file:
.B $ cat commands.txt | ./hsh

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sh (1),
.BR bash (1),
.BR execve (2),
.BR fork (2),
.BR wait (2),
.BR getline (3),
.BR strtok (3)

